  poem:
    text: "Rangstreit of Hashish and Wine\n\nMay all be well with you! Do not listen
      to the word of the old censor And do not let not following tradition shape
      your legal decisions. You have asked about the relationship between the green
      one and wine. Thus listen to What a person of correct and straightforward views
      has to say.\n\nYou ought to obtain it, a green one, not to be acquired at an
      excessive price For the white of silver or the red of gold. It is something
      belonging to meadows whose greenness resembles the gardens (of Paradise).\n\nIt
      is the secret. In it, the spirit ascends to the highest Spots on a heavenly
      ascent (mi\u02BFr\u0101j) of disembodied understanding.\n\nYou find yourself
      clean, virtuous, bright,\nWitty, and unencumbered by excessive dullness.\n\nAmong
      its excellent medical qualities is that it is good for digestion.\nHow impossible
      it is to enumerate all its manifold virtues!\n\nDo not listen to what critics
      may say with respect to it. They want to keep you away from it. Disobey any
      old censor!\n\nAl-Is\u02BFird\u012B"
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  contextInfos:
  - text: "# Arabic poem agains hashish\nO you who are similar to dumb beasts, having
      become like an ox grazing on cannabis hashish!\n\nIndeed, you are more similar
      to a dumb beast. Only you have distanced yourself from it by wearing cloth
      it does not wear.\n\nThe drug has settled down in you, and through its intoxication
      you have turned to walking as does someone born blind, feeling his way.\n\nThe
      face resembles in its compact weave Garments of smooth, ma\u02BFdin\u012B silk.\n\nDoes
      it please you, hapless man, to be seen among mankind blind and deaf, using
      sign language like a deaf person?\n\nQuite often has it been eaten in a privy
      out of fear of an observer and vileness in the souls."
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  - text: '#The Travels of Marco Polo, Book 1, Chapter XXIII XXIV, The Complete Yule
      Cordier Edition

      "The Old Man was called in their language Aloadin. He
      had caused a certain valley between two mountains to be enclosed, and had turned
      it into a garden [...] filled with every variety of fruit. In it were erected
      pavilions and palaces [...] all covered with gilding and exquisite painting.
      And there were runnels too, flowing freely with wine and milk and honey and
      water; and numbers of [...] the most beautiful damsels in the world [...] For
      the Old Man desired to make his people believe that this was actually Paradise.
      [...] Now no man was allowed to enter the Garden save those whom he intended
      to be his Ashishin. [...] He kept at his Court a number of the youths of the
      country, from 12 to 20 years of age [...] Then he would introduce them into
      his garden [...] having first made them drink a certain potion which cast them
      into a deep sleep [...] So when they awoke, they found themselves in the Garden.
      [...] And when he wanted one of his Ashishin to send on any mission, he would
      cause that potion [...] to be given to one of the youths in the garden, and
      then had him carried into his Palace. [...] So when the Old Man would have
      any Prince slain, he would say to such a youth: ''Go thou and slay So and So;
      and when thou returnest my Angels shall bear thee into Paradise. [...]'' [...]
      and thus there was no order of his that they would not affront any peril to
      execute, for the great desire they had to get back into that Paradise of his."'
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  - text: "Igziabeher (Let Jah be Praised) \u2013 Peter Tosh\nVerse 1:\n\nHe watereth
      the hills from his chambers\nAnd the Earth is satisfied, so satisfied\nHe maketh
      the grass to grow for animals\nJah made the herb for man\nHe made the herb
      for man\nJah made the herb for man\n\nFor Rastafari, cannabis is a sacrament
      rather than a recreation, smoked in prayer and reasoning sessions to aid meditation
      and bring the user closer to Jah (God, from Jehova). Its use is often grounded
      in scripture, read as the \"herb\" given for the service and healing of humankind.\n\nPsalm
      104:13-14\n\n13 He watereth the hills from His chambers; the earth is satisfied
      with the fruit of Thy works.\n\n14 He causeth the grass to grow for the cattle
      and herbs for the service of man, that he may bring forth food out of the earth,"
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
